[2026-03-13T14:38:52Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NXGojP78AcDd4xWfR5yVEm","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20→\n    21→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26→\n    27→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29→\n    30→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31→object with the following fields:\n    32→\n    33→| Field | Required | Description |\n    34→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40→\n    41→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44→reassignment.\n    45→\n    46→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47→file is a parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## Concepts\n    50→\n    51→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    58→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    59→\n    60→## Step Types\n    61→\n    62→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63→\n    64→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67→\n    68→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70→\n    71→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73→\n    74→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75→parse error.\n    76→\n    77→## DSL Syntax\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→workflow \"develop\" {\n    81→  container {\n    82→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    83→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    84→  }\n    85→\n    86→  step implement {\n    87→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88→    results = [success, fail]\n    89→  }\n    90→\n    91→  step test {\n    92→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    93→    results = [success, fail]\n    94→  }\n    95→\n    96→  step fix {\n    97→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    98→    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    99→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   100→  }\n   101→\n   102→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   103→  implement:success -> test\n   104→  implement:fail    -> abort\n   105→  test:success      -> done\n   106→  test:fail         -> fix\n   107→  fix:success       -> test\n   108→  fix:fail          -> abort\n   109→  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   110→}\n   111→```\n   112→\n   113→## Key Properties\n   114→\n   115→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   116→field makes it a script step.\n   117→\n   118→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   119→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   120→\n   121→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   122→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   123→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   124→\n   125→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   126→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   127→\n   128→## Wire Output Mappings\n   129→\n   130→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   131→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→The general form:\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   144→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   145→\n   146→| Expression | Meaning |\n   147→|---|---|\n   148→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   149→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   150→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   151→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   152→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   153→\n   154→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   155→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   156→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   157→\n   158→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   159→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   160→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   161→\n   162→## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   163→\n   164→Workflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   165→steps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   166→\n   167→**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   168→network allowlist.\n   169→\n   170→```\n   171→workflow \"develop\" {\n   172→  container {\n   173→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   174→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   175→    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   176→  }\n   177→  ...\n   178→}\n   179→```\n   180→\n   181→Supported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   182→\n   183→**`host {}`** — For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\n   184→running on the host machine.\n   185→\n   186→```\n   187→workflow \"main\" {\n   188→  host {\n   189→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   190→  }\n   191→  ...\n   192→}\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   196→\n   197→Step-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   198→resolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   199→var > default `claude`.\n   200→\n   201→## Host Workflow Example\n   202→\n   203→A three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   204→workflows:\n   205→\n   206→```\n   207→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   208→\n   209→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   210→  step fetch-tickets {\n   211→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   212→    results = [success, fail]\n   213→  }\n   214→\n   215→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   216→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   217→}\n   218→\n   219→workflow \"main\" {\n   220→  host {\n   221→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   222→  }\n   223→\n   224→  step prepare-prompt {\n   225→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   226→    results = [success, fail]\n   227→  }\n   228→\n   229→  step develop {\n   230→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   231→    results       = [success, fail]\n   232→  }\n   233→\n   234→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   235→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   236→  develop:success        -> done\n   237→  develop:fail           -> done\n   238→}\n   239→\n   240→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   241→  step push-for-review {\n   242→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   243→    results = [success, fail]\n   244→  }\n   245→\n   246→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   247→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   248→}\n   249→```\n   250→\n   251→The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   252→runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   253→The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   254→The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   255→The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   256→`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   257→\n   258→## Execution Model\n   259→\n   260→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   261→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   262→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   263→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   264→\n   265→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   266→`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   267→in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   268→working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   269→if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   270→host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   271→runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   272→`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   273→points to the actual project directory.\n   274→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017xCxwq7vtimYnzVCvKMfnj","session_id":"aeb114c6-22ff-4078-baec-d21a69457fa7","uuid":"abcc5df5-918e-414d-8347-ee05afe597f0"}
