[2026-03-13T14:38:52Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013gArkNVNaufS9zKADi4AFc","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Ruby Calculator\n     2→\n     3→A Ruby arithmetic expression parser and evaluator, built entirely by\n     4→[Cloche](../../README.md) — an autonomous workflow system for coding agents.\n     5→\n     6→## What it does\n     7→\n     8→```ruby\n     9→calc = Calculator.new\n    10→calc.evaluate(\"2 + 3 * (4 - 1)\")  # => 11.0\n    11→calc.evaluate(\"-(3 + 2) * 2\")     # => -10.0\n    12→calc.evaluate(\"3.14 * 2\")         # => 6.28\n    13→```\n    14→\n    15→Supports `+`, `-`, `*`, `/` with correct operator precedence, parentheses,\n    16→decimal numbers, and negative numbers. Uses a recursive descent parser — no\n    17→`eval()`.\n    18→\n    19→## How this was built\n    20→\n    21→This project was generated in a single Cloche workflow run. No human wrote any\n    22→of the Ruby code. The command:\n    23→\n    24→```\n    25→cloche run --workflow develop --prompt '<prompt>'\n    26→```\n    27→\n    28→The prompt passed to Cloche:\n    29→\n    30→> Build a Ruby calculator application that parses and evaluates arithmetic\n    31→> expressions from string input. Requirements:\n    32→>\n    33→> 1. A Calculator class with an evaluate(expression) method that takes a string like \"2 + 3 * (4 - 1)\" and returns the numeric result as a float\n    34→> 2. Support operators: +, -, *, / with correct operator precedence (* and / bind tighter than + and -)\n    35→> 3. Support parentheses for grouping subexpressions\n    36→> 4. Support integer and decimal numbers, including negative numbers like -5 or -(3+2)\n    37→> 5. Raise meaningful errors for: mismatched parentheses, division by zero, invalid tokens\n    38→> 6. Use a recursive descent parser (tokenizer -> parser -> evaluator), not eval()\n    39→> 7. A Gemfile listing minitest and rubocop as dependencies\n    40→> 8. A Rakefile with default task running tests\n    41→> 9. Comprehensive minitest tests covering: basic ops, precedence, nested parens, decimals, negative numbers, whitespace handling, and all error cases\n    42→> 10. A .rubocop.yml with reasonable defaults\n    43→>\n    44→> All source files go in lib/, tests in test/.\n    45→\n    46→## The workflow\n    47→\n    48→The `develop.cloche` workflow defines the full build-test-fix pipeline:\n    49→\n    50→```\n    51→implement → test → lint ──────┐\n    52→                └→ quality ───┤ collect all → done\n    53→                              │\n    54→           ┌──── fix ←────────┘ (on any failure)\n    55→           └→ test (retry loop, max 2 fix attempts)\n    56→```\n    57→\n    58→1. **implement** — Claude Code writes all project files inside a Docker\n    59→   container based on the prompt\n    60→2. **test** — `bundle exec rake test` runs the minitest suite\n    61→3. **lint** + **quality** run concurrently:\n    62→   - **lint** — `bundle exec rubocop` checks style\n    63→   - **quality** — [speedometer](https://github.com/your-org/speedometer)\n    64→     scores the git diff for code quality signals\n    65→4. **fix** — if lint or quality fails, Claude Code gets the failure output and\n    66→   fixes the code (max 2 attempts)\n    67→5. After fix, the pipeline re-runs from **test**\n    68→\n    69→### Actual execution trace\n    70→\n    71→| Step | Result | Notes |\n    72→|------|--------|-------|\n    73→| implement | success | Wrote calculator, tests, Gemfile, Rakefile, .rubocop.yml |\n    74→| test | success | 45 tests passed on first attempt |\n    75→| lint | fail | rubocop found style issues |\n    76→| quality | success | speedometer scored the diff clean |\n    77→| fix | success | Claude Code fixed the lint violations |\n    78→| test | success | re-validated after fix |\n    79→| lint | success | clean on second pass |\n    80→| quality | success | still clean |\n    81→| **collect all** | **done** | ~4 minutes total |\n    82→\n    83→## Run artifacts\n    84→\n    85→The `.cloche/` directory is created at runtime and contains the full state of\n    86→the workflow run. It's checked in here as documentation of how the run\n    87→progressed.\n    88→\n    89→```\n    90→.cloche/\n    91→  prompt.txt              # The user prompt passed via --prompt\n    92→  output/\n    93→    test.log              # stdout from the test step (final pass)\n    94→    lint.log              # stdout from the lint step (final pass)\n    95→    quality.log           # stdout from the quality step\n    96→  attempt_count/\n    97→    implement             # \"1\" — implement ran once\n    98→    fix                   # \"1\" — fix ran once (lint failed, fix succeeded)\n    99→```\n   100→\n   101→`prompt.txt` is the input — the user's request injected into the agent's prompt\n   102→template. The `output/*.log` files are the outputs — captured from each script\n   103→step and fed back to the fix agent when something fails. `attempt_count/` tracks\n   104→how many times each step has been invoked, used to enforce `max_attempts` limits.\n   105→\n   106→The logs here reflect the **final successful pass** (after the fix step resolved\n   107→the lint issues):\n   108→\n   109→**test.log** — 45 tests, 47 assertions, 0 failures:\n   110→```\n   111→Finished in 0.002216s, 20305.9061 runs/s, 21208.3908 assertions/s.\n   112→45 runs, 47 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 skips\n   113→```\n   114→\n   115→**lint.log** — clean:\n   116→```\n   117→4 files inspected, no offenses detected\n   118→```\n   119→\n   120→**quality.log** — no diff to score (all files were new/untracked):\n   121→```\n   122→No changes to score.\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→## Running locally\n   126→\n   127→```\n   128→bundle install\n   129→bundle exec rake test\n   130→```\n   131→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017xCxwq7vtimYnzVCvKMfnj","session_id":"aeb114c6-22ff-4078-baec-d21a69457fa7","uuid":"b6773067-7431-49a8-98