[2026-03-13T14:41:35Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LCYvbMZt1RDVHuYD3meZN1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# How to Set Up Codex\n     2→\n     3→This guide covers configuring Cloche containers to use\n     4→[OpenAI Codex](https://platform.openai.com/docs) as the coding agent.\n     5→\n     6→## Prerequisites\n     7→\n     8→- A working Cloche installation ([Installation guide](INSTALL.md))\n     9→- An OpenAI API key with Codex access\n    10→\n    11→## How Authentication Works\n    12→\n    13→Unlike Claude Code, Codex authenticates via an API key rather than a local session.\n    14→You pass your OpenAI API key into containers using environment variables.\n    15→\n    16→## Dockerfile\n    17→\n    18→Your `.cloche/Dockerfile` must install the Codex CLI:\n    19→\n    20→```dockerfile\n    21→FROM cloche-base:latest\n    22→USER root\n    23→\n    24→# Install Node.js (required for Codex CLI)\n    25→RUN apt-get update \\\n    26→    && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends nodejs npm \\\n    27→    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n    28→\n    29→# Install Codex CLI\n    30→RUN npm install -g @openai/codex\n    31→\n    32→# Add your project's build dependencies here\n    33→# RUN apt-get install -y ...\n    34→\n    35→USER agent\n    36→```\n    37→\n    38→## Passing the API Key\n    39→\n    40→Set `OPENAI_API_KEY` using `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` in the daemon's environment:\n    41→\n    42→```bash\n    43→export CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV=\"OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\"\n    44→cloched &\n    45→```\n    46→\n    47→`CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` accepts comma-separated `KEY=VALUE` pairs and injects them into\n    48→every container.\n    49→\n    50→## Workflow Configuration\n    51→\n    52→Set `agent_command` to `codex` at the workflow or step level:\n    53→\n    54→**Workflow level** (applies to all steps):\n    55→\n    56→```\n    57→workflow \"develop\" {\n    58→  container {\n    59→    agent_command = \"codex\"\n    60→  }\n    61→\n    62→  step implement {\n    63→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    64→    results = [success, fail]\n    65→  }\n    66→\n    67→  implement:success -> done\n    68→  implement:fail -> abort\n    69→}\n    70→```\n    71→\n    72→**Step level** (per-step override):\n    73→\n    74→```\n    75→step implement {\n    76→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    77→  agent_command = \"codex\"\n    78→  results = [success, fail]\n    79→}\n    80→```\n    81→\n    82→Codex is not a \"known\" agent in Cloche, so it receives the prompt on stdin with no\n    83→default arguments. Add `agent_args` if the Codex CLI needs specific flags:\n    84→\n    85→```\n    86→step implement {\n    87→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88→  agent_command = \"codex\"\n    89→  agent_args = \"--full-auto\"\n    90→  results = [success, fail]\n    91→}\n    92→```\n    93→\n    94→## Fallback Chains\n    95→\n    96→Use Codex as a fallback if Claude is unavailable:\n    97→\n    98→```\n    99→agent_command = \"claude,codex\"\n   100→```\n   101→\n   102→Or use Codex as the primary with Claude as fallback:\n   103→\n   104→```\n   105→agent_command = \"codex,claude\"\n   106→```\n   107→\n   108→See [Agent Command Resolution](USAGE.md#agent-command-resolution) for full fallback\n   109→semantics.\n   110→\n   111→## Verifying the Setup\n   112→\n   113→Run a quick test workflow:\n   114→\n   115→```bash\n   116→cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Print hello world\"\n   117→```\n   118→\n   119→Check logs to confirm Codex is executing:\n   120→\n   121→```bash\n   122→cloche logs <run-id>\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→## Troubleshooting\n   126→\n   127→**Codex not found in container**: Make sure your Dockerfile installs `@openai/codex`\n   128→via npm and that Node.js is available.\n   129→\n   130→**Authentication errors**: Verify that `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` includes a valid\n   131→`OPENAI_API_KEY`. You can check by inspecting the container's environment:\n   132→\n   133→```bash\n   134→docker exec <container-id> env | grep OPENAI\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→**No output from Codex**: Since Codex is not a known agent, Cloche passes the prompt\n   138→on stdin. Ensure the Codex CLI version you installed supports reading prompts from\n   139→stdin, or set appropriate `agent_args`.\n   140→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8ea6a4db-317b-4116-946b-dfa5f420f957","uuid":"754ed318-fb08-4602-87d1-90171c78471c","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/agent-setup-codex.md","content":"# How to Set Up Codex\n\nThis guide covers configuring Cloche containers to use\n[OpenAI Codex](https://platform.openai.com/docs) as the coding agent.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\n- A working Cloche installation ([Installation guide](INSTALL.md))\n- An OpenAI API key with Codex access\n\n## How Authentication Works\n\nUnlike Claude Code, Codex authenticates via an API key rather than a local session.\nYou pass your OpenAI API key into containers using environment variables.\n\n## Dockerfile\n\nYour `.cloche/Dockerfile` must install the Codex CLI:\n\n```dockerfile\nFROM cloche-base:latest\nUSER root\n\n# Install Node.js (required for Codex CLI)\nRUN apt-get update \\\n    && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends nodejs npm \\\n    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n\n# Install Codex CLI\nRUN npm install -g @openai/codex\n\n# Add your project's build dependencies here\n# RUN apt-get install -y ...\n\nUSER agent\n```\n\n## Passing the API Key\n\nSet `OPENAI_API_KEY` using `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` in the daemon's environment:\n\n```bash\nexport CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV=\"OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\"\ncloched &\n```\n\n`CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` accepts comma-separated `KEY=VALUE` pairs and injects them into\nevery container.\n\n## Workflow Configuration\n\nSet `agent_command` to `codex` at the workflow or step level:\n\n**Workflow level** (applies to all steps):\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    agent_command = \"codex\"\n  }\n\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> done\n  implement:fail -> abort\n}\n```\n\n**Step level** (per-step override):\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  agent_command = \"codex\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\nCodex is not a \"known\" agent in Cloche, so it receives the prompt on stdin with no\ndefault arguments. Add `agent_args` if the Codex CLI needs specific flags:\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  agent_command = \"codex\"\n  agent_args = \"--full-auto\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n## Fallback Chains\n\nUse Codex as a fallback if Claude is unavailable:\n\n```\nagent_command = \"claude,codex\"\n```\n\nOr use Codex as the primary with Claude as fallback:\n\n```\nagent_command = \"codex,claude\"\n```\n\nSee [Agent Command Resolution](USAGE.md#agent-command-resolution) for full fallback\nsemantics.\n\n## Verifying the Setup\n\nRun a quick test workflow:\n\n```bash\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Print hello world\"\n```\n\nCheck logs to confirm Codex is executing:\n\n```bash\ncloche logs <run-id>\n```\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n**Codex not found in container**: Make sure your Dockerfile installs `@openai/codex`\nvia npm and that Node.js is available.\n\n**Authentication errors**: Verify that `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` includes a valid\n`OPENAI_API_KEY`. You can check by inspecting the container's environment:\n\n```bash\ndocker exec <container-id> env | grep OPENAI\n```\n\n**No output from Codex**: Since Codex is not a known agent, Cloche passes the prompt\non stdin. Ensure the Codex CLI version you installed supports reading prompts from\nstdin, or set appropriate `agent_args`.\n","numLines":140,"startLine":1,"totalLines":140}}}
